{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584764","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584764"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:56:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:56:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14799"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14799","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14799"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.03,0.77,0.1,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7490"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75570"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7490","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7490"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14799"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61087"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5174"},{"type":"tags","id":"10292"},{"type":"tags","id":"10293"},{"type":"tags","id":"10315"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18329"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21767"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75570","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75570"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAlzheimer\u0027s disease is characterised by progressive cognitive decline and memory loss. Several medications are used to manage symptoms of this condition.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of action of acetylcholinesterase inhibitors in the treatment of Alzheimer disease?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Blocks acetylcholine release from presynaptic neurons","Increases acetylcholine vesicle formation","Inhibits acetylcholine breakdown in synapses","Stimulates acetylcholine synthesis","Blocks acetylcholine receptors"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary mechanism of action of acetylcholinesterase inhibitors is \u003Cstrong\u003Einhibition of acetylcholine breakdown in synapses\u003C/strong\u003E. This leads to increased acetylcholine concentration and duration of action in synaptic clefts, helping to compensate for the reduced cholinergic function seen in Alzheimer disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking acetylcholine release\u003C/strong\u003E would worsen symptoms by reducing cholinergic transmission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulating acetylcholine synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E is not a known mechanism of acetylcholinesterase inhibitors; instead, they preserve existing acetylcholine by preventing breakdown.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking acetylcholine receptors\u003C/strong\u003E would oppose the desired effect of increasing cholinergic transmission and subsequently worsen symptoms of Alzheimer disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing acetylcholine vesicle formation\u003C/strong\u003E is not the mechanism of acetylcholinesterase inhibitors, as these drugs work by preventing breakdown of released acetylcholine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECommon acetylcholinesterase inhibitors used in Alzheimer\u0027s disease include donepezil, rivastigmine, and galantamine. These medications can provide modest symptomatic benefit but do not alter disease progression.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acetylcholinesterase inhibitors work by increasing acetylcholine levels in synapses by preventing its breakdown.","Donepezil, rivastigmine, and galantamine are the main acetylcholinesterase inhibitors used to treat Alzheimer disease.","Memantine works through a different mechanism by antagonising N-methyl-D-aspartate (NMDA) receptors."],"references":["Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61087"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14799"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61087","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61087"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-30T11:31:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T13:06:13+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7490"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75570"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position